# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: vagrant
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:vagrant/development-environment-software-development-process] In software deployment, an **environment** or **tier** is a computer system or set of systems in which a computer program or software component is deployed and executed.
[src:vagrant/development-environment-software-development-process] This structured release management process allows phased deployment (rollout), testing, and rollback in case of problems.
[src:vagrant/development-environment-software-development-process] Environments may vary significantly in size: the development environment is typically an individual developer's workstation, while the production environment may be a network of many geographically distributed machines in data centers, or virtual machines in cloud computing.
[src:vagrant/development-environment-software-development-process] Code, data, and configuration may be deployed in parallel, and need not connect to the corresponding tier—for example, pre-production code might connect to a production database.
[src:vagrant/development-environment-software-development-process] Deployment architectures vary significantly, but, broadly, the tiers are bookended by starting at *development* (DEV) and ending at *production* (PROD).
[src:vagrant/development-environment-software-development-process] A common 4-tier architecture is *development, testing, model, production* (DEV, TEST, MODL, PROD), with software being deployed to each in order.
[src:vagrant/development-environment-software-development-process] Other common environments include Quality Control (QC), for acceptance testing; sandbox or experimental (EXP), for experiments that are not intended to proceed to production; and Disaster Recovery, to provide an immediate fallback in case of problems with production.
[src:vagrant/development-environment-software-development-process] Another common architecture is development, testing, acceptance and production (DTAP).
[src:vagrant/development-environment-software-development-process] This language is particularly suited for server programs, where servers run in a remote data center; for code that runs on an end user's device, such as applications (apps) or clients, one can refer to the user environment (USER) or local environment (LOCAL) instead.
[src:vagrant/development-environment-software-development-process] Exact definitions and boundaries between environments vary – test may be considered part of dev, Acceptance may be considered part of test, part of stage, or be separate, etc.
[src:vagrant/development-environment-software-development-process] The main tiers are progressed through in order, with new releases being deployed (*rolled out* or *pushed*) to each in turn.
[src:vagrant/development-environment-software-development-process] Experimental and recovery tiers, if present, are outside this flow – experimental releases are terminal, while recovery is typically an old or duplicate version of production, deployed after production.
[src:vagrant/development-environment-software-development-process] In case of problems, one can *roll back* to the old release, most simply by pushing the old release as if it were a new release.
[src:vagrant/development-environment-software-development-process] The last step, deploying to production ("pushing to prod") is the most sensitive, as any problems result in immediate user impact.
[src:vagrant/development-environment-software-development-process] For this is often handled differently, at least being monitored more carefully, and in some cases having phased rollout or only requiring flipping a switch, allowing rapid rollback.
[src:vagrant/development-environment-software-development-process] It is best to avoid a name like Quality Assurance (QA); QA doesn’t mean software testing.
[src:vagrant/development-environment-software-development-process] Testing is important, but it is different from QA.
[src:vagrant/development-environment-software-development-process] Sometimes deployment is done outside of this regular process, primarily to provide urgent or relatively minor changes, without requiring a full release.
[src:vagrant/development-environment-software-development-process] This may consist of a single patch, a large service pack, or a small hotfix.
[src:vagrant/development-environment-software-development-process] The table below describes a finely-divided list of tiers.
[src:vagrant/development-environment-software-development-process] The development environment (dev) is the environment in which changes to software are developed, most simply an individual developer's workstation.
[src:vagrant/development-environment-software-development-process] The environment on an individual workstation, in which changes are worked on and tried out, may be referred to as the *local environment* or a sandbox.
[src:vagrant/development-environment-software-development-process] The purpose of the test environment is to allow human testers to exercise new and changed code via either automated checks or non-automated techniques.
[src:vagrant/development-environment-software-development-process] After the developer accepts the new code and configurations through unit testing in the development environment, the items are moved to one or more test environments.
[src:vagrant/development-environment-software-development-process] Upon test failure, the test environment can remove the faulty code from the test platforms, contact the responsible developer, and provide detailed test and result logs.
[src:vagrant/development-environment-software-development-process] If all tests pass, the test environment or a continuous integration framework controlling the tests can automatically promote the code to the next deployment environment.
[src:vagrant/development-environment-software-development-process] Different types of testing suggest different types of test environments, some or all of which may be virtualized to allow rapid, parallel testing to take place.
[src:vagrant/development-environment-software-development-process] For example, automated user interface tests may occur across several virtual operating systems and displays (real or virtual).
[src:vagrant/development-environment-software-development-process] Performance tests may require a normalized physical baseline hardware configuration, so that performance test results can be compared over time.
[src:vagrant/development-environment-software-development-process] Availability or durability testing may depend on failure simulators in virtual hardware and virtual networks.
[src:vagrant/development-environment-software-development-process] Tests may be serial (one after the other) or parallel (some or all at once) depending on the sophistication of the test environment.
[src:vagrant/development-environment-software-development-process] A significant goal for agile and other high-productivity software development practices is reducing the time from software design or specification to delivery in production.
[src:vagrant/development-environment-software-development-process] Highly automated and parallelized test environments are important contributors to rapid software development.
[src:vagrant/development-environment-software-development-process] A stage, staging or pre-production environment is an environment for testing that exactly resembles a production environment.
[src:vagrant/development-environment-software-development-process] It seeks to mirror an actual production environment as closely as possible and may connect to other production services and data, such as databases.
[src:vagrant/development-environment-software-development-process] For example, servers will be run on remote machines, rather than locally (as on a developer's workstation during dev, or on a single test machine during the test), which tests the effects of networking on the system.
[src:vagrant/development-environment-software-development-process] The primary use of a staging environment is to test all the installation/configuration/migration scripts and procedures before they're applied to a production environment.
[src:vagrant/development-environment-software-development-process] This ensures all major and minor upgrades to a production environment are completed reliably, without errors, and in a minimum of time.
[src:vagrant/development-environment-software-development-process] Another important use of staging is performance testing, particularly load testing, as this is often sensitive to the environment.
[src:vagrant/development-environment-software-development-process] Staging is also used by some organizations to preview new features to select customers or to validate integrations with live versions of external dependencies.
[src:vagrant/development-environment-software-development-process] The production environment is also known as *live*, particularly for servers, as it is the environment that users directly interact with.
[src:vagrant/development-environment-software-development-process] Deploying to production is the most sensitive step; it may be done by deploying new code directly (overwriting old code, so only one copy is present at a time), or by deploying a configuration change.
[src:vagrant/development-environment-software-development-process] These in turn may be done all at once or gradually, in phases.
[src:vagrant/development-environment-software-development-process] When deploying a new release to production, rather than immediately deploying to all instances or users, it may be deployed to a single instance or fraction of users first, and then either deployed to all or gradually deployed in phases, in order to catch any last-minute problems.
[src:vagrant/development-environment-software-development-process] This is similar to staging, except actually done in production, and is referred to as a *canary release*, by analogy with coal mining.
[src:vagrant/development-environment-software-development-process] This adds complexity due to multiple releases being run simultaneously, and is thus usually over quickly, to avoid compatibility problems.
[src:vagrant/development-environment-software-development-process] Development, Staging and Production are known and documented environment variables in ASP.NET Core.
[src:vagrant/development-environment-software-development-process] Depending on the defined variable, different code is executed and content rendered, and different security and debug settings are applied.
[src:vagrant/hashicorp] HashiCorp is headquartered in San Francisco, but its employees are distributed across the United States, Canada, Australia, India, and Europe.
[src:vagrant/hashicorp] HashiCorp offers source-available libraries and other proprietary products.
[src:vagrant/hashicorp] HashiCorp was founded in 2012 by Mitchell Hashimoto and Armon Dadgar, two classmates from the University of Washington's Paul G.
[src:vagrant/hashicorp] Allen School of Computer Science and Engineering .
[src:vagrant/hashicorp] Co-founder Hashimoto was previously working on open-source software called Vagrant, which became incorporated into HashiCorp.
[src:vagrant/hashicorp] On 29 November 2021, HashiCorp set terms for its IPO at $68-$72 at a valuation of $13 billion.
[src:vagrant/hashicorp] HashiCorp considers its workers to be remote workers first rather than coming into an office on a full-time basis.
[src:vagrant/hashicorp] Around April 2021, a supply chain attack using code auditing tool codecov allowed hackers limited access to HashiCorp's customers networks.
[src:vagrant/hashicorp] As a result, private credentials were leaked.
[src:vagrant/hashicorp] HashiCorp revoked a private signing key and asked its customers to use a new rotated key.
[src:vagrant/hashicorp] Mitchell Hashimoto resigned from the company in December 2023.
[src:vagrant/hashicorp] On April 24, 2024, the company announced it had entered into an agreement to be acquired by IBM for $6.4 billion, with the transaction expected to close by the end of the same year.
[src:vagrant/hashicorp] This led to the Competition and Markets Authority of the United Kingdom launching an investigation into the acquisition in late 2024.
[src:vagrant/hashicorp] The deal closed on February 27, 2025 for $6.4 billion after receiving the necessary regulatory approvals.
[src:vagrant/hashicorp] HashiCorp provides a suite of tools intended to support the development and deployment of large-scale service-oriented software installations.
[src:vagrant/hashicorp] Each tool is aimed at specific stages in the life cycle of a software application, with a focus on automation.
[src:vagrant/hashicorp] Many have a plugin-oriented architecture in order to provide integration with third-party technologies and services.
[src:vagrant/hashicorp] Additional proprietary features for some of these tools are offered commercially and are aimed at enterprise customers.
[src:vagrant/vagrant-intro] Vagrant is a tool for building complete development environments.
[src:vagrant/vagrant-intro] With an easy-to-use workflow and focus on automation, Vagrant lowers development environment setup time, increases development/production parity, and makes the "it works on my machine" excuse a relic of the past.
[src:vagrant/vagrant-intro] Vagrant is a tool for building and managing virtual machine environments in a single workflow.
[src:vagrant/vagrant-intro] With an easy-to-use workflow and focus on automation, Vagrant lowers development environment setup time, increases production parity, and makes the "works on my machine" excuse a relic of the past.
[src:vagrant/vagrant-intro] If you are already familiar with the basics of Vagrant, the documentation provides a better reference build for all available features and internals.
[src:vagrant/vagrant-intro] Vagrant provides easy to configure, reproducible, and portable work environments built on top of industry-standard technology and controlled by a single consistent workflow to help maximize the productivity and flexibility of you and your team.
[src:vagrant/vagrant-intro] To achieve its magic, Vagrant stands on the shoulders of giants.
[src:vagrant/vagrant-intro] Machines are provisioned on top of VirtualBox, VMware, AWS, or any other provider.
[src:vagrant/vagrant-intro] Then, industry-standard provisioning tools such as shell scripts, Chef, or Puppet can automatically install and configure software on the virtual machine.
[src:vagrant/vagrant-intro] If you are a **developer**, Vagrant will isolate dependencies and their configuration within a single disposable, consistent environment, without sacrificing any of the tools you are used to working with (editors, browsers, debuggers, etc.).
[src:vagrant/vagrant-intro] Once you or someone else creates a single Vagrantfile, you just need to `vagrant up` and everything is installed and configured for you to work.
[src:vagrant/vagrant-intro] Other members of your team create their development environments from the same configuration, so whether you are working on Linux, Mac OS X, or Windows, all your team members are running code in the same environment, against the same dependencies, all configured the same way.
[src:vagrant/vagrant-intro] Say goodbye to "works on my machine" bugs.
[src:vagrant/vagrant-intro] If you are an **operations engineer** or **DevOps engineer**, Vagrant gives you a disposable environment and consistent workflow for developing and testing infrastructure management scripts.
[src:vagrant/vagrant-intro] You can quickly test things like shell scripts, Chef cookbooks, Puppet modules, and more using local virtualization such as VirtualBox or VMware.
[src:vagrant/vagrant-intro] Then, with the *same configuration*, you can test these scripts on remote clouds such as AWS or RackSpace with the *same workflow*.
[src:vagrant/vagrant-intro] Ditch your custom scripts to recycle EC2 instances, stop juggling SSH prompts to various machines, and start using Vagrant to bring sanity to your life.
[src:vagrant/vagrant-intro] If you are a **designer**, Vagrant will automatically set everything up that is required for that web app in order for you to focus on doing what you do best: design.
[src:vagrant/vagrant-intro] Once a developer configures Vagrant, you do not need to worry about how to get that app running ever again.
[src:vagrant/vagrant-intro] No more bothering other developers to help you fix your environment so you can test designs.
[src:vagrant/vagrant-intro] Just check out the code, `vagrant up`, and start designing.
[src:vagrant/vagrant-intro] Vagrant is designed for everyone as the easiest and fastest way to create a virtualized environment!
[src:vagrant/vagrant-software] Vagrant was first started as a personal side-project by Mitchell Hashimoto in January 2010.
[src:vagrant/vagrant-software] The first version of Vagrant was released in March 2010.
[src:vagrant/vagrant-software] In October 2010, Engine Yard declared that they were going to sponsor the Vagrant project.
[src:vagrant/vagrant-software] The first stable version, Vagrant 1.0, was released in March 2012, exactly two years after the original version was released.
[src:vagrant/vagrant-software] In November 2012, Mitchell formed an organization called HashiCorp to support the full-time development of Vagrant; Vagrant remained permissively licensed free software.
[src:vagrant/vagrant-software] HashiCorp now works on creating commercial editions and provides professional support and training for Vagrant.
[src:vagrant/vagrant-software] Vagrant was originally tied to VirtualBox, but version 1.1 added support for other virtualization software such as VMware and KVM, and for server environments like Amazon EC2.
[src:vagrant/vagrant-software] Vagrant is written in Ruby, but it can be used in projects written in other programming languages such as PHP, Python, Java, C#, and JavaScript.
[src:vagrant/vagrant-software] Since version 1.6, Vagrant natively supports Docker containers, which in some cases can serve as a substitute for a fully virtualized operating system.
[src:vagrant/vagrant-software] Vagrant uses "Provisioners" and "Providers" as building blocks to manage the development environments.
[src:vagrant/vagrant-software] Provisioners are tools that allow users to customize the configuration of virtual environments.
[src:vagrant/vagrant-software] Puppet and Chef are the two most widely used provisioners in the Vagrant ecosystem (Ansible has been available since at least 2014).
[src:vagrant/vagrant-software] Providers are the services that Vagrant uses to set up and create virtual environments.
[src:vagrant/vagrant-software] Support for VirtualBox, Hyper-V, and Docker virtualization ships with Vagrant, while VMware and AWS are supported via plugins.
[src:vagrant/vagrant-software] Vagrant sits on top of virtualization software as a wrapper and helps the developer interact easily with the providers.
[src:vagrant/vagrant-software] It automates the configuration of virtual environments using Chef or Puppet, and the user does not have to directly use any other virtualization software.
[src:vagrant/vagrant-software] Machine and software requirements are written in a file called "Vagrantfile" to execute necessary steps in order to create a development-ready box.
[src:vagrant/vagrant-software] "Box" is a format and an extension (.box) for Vagrant environments that is copied to another machine in order to replicate the same environment.
[src:vagrant/vagrant-software] The official Vagrant documentation details the installation, command line usage, and relevant configuration of Vagrant.
[src:vagrant/vagrant-software] HashiCorp announced on Aug 10, 2023 that it changed the license of Vagrant from the MIT license to the Business Source License 1.1.
[src:vagrant/vagrant] Vagrant is the command line utility for managing the lifecycle of virtual machines.
[src:vagrant/vagrant] HCP Vagrant Registry serves a public, searchable index of Vagrant boxes.
[src:vagrant/virtualbox] VirtualBox may be installed on Microsoft Windows, macOS, Linux, Solaris and OpenSolaris.
[src:vagrant/virtualbox] There are also ports to FreeBSD and Genode.
[src:vagrant/virtualbox] It supports the creation and management of guest virtual machines running Windows, Linux, BSD, OS/2, Solaris, Haiku, and OSx86, as well as limited virtualization of macOS guests on Apple hardware.
[src:vagrant/virtualbox] Released under the terms of the GNU General Public License and, optionally, the CDDL for most files of the source distribution, VirtualBox is free and open-source software, though the Extension Pack is proprietary software, free of charge only to personal users.
[src:vagrant/virtualbox] The license to VirtualBox was relicensed to GPLv3 with linking exceptions to the CDDL and other GPL-incompatible licenses.
[src:vagrant/virtualbox] VirtualBox was first offered by InnoTek Systemberatung GmbH, a German company based in Weinstadt, under a proprietary software license, making one version of the product available at no cost for personal or evaluation use, subject to the VirtualBox Personal Use and Evaluation License (PUEL).
[src:vagrant/virtualbox] In January 2007, based on counsel by LiSoG, InnoTek released VirtualBox Open Source Edition (OSE) as free and open-source software, subject to the requirements of the GNU General Public License (GPL), version 2.
[src:vagrant/virtualbox] InnoTek also contributed to the development of OS/2 and Linux support in virtualization and OS/2 ports of products from Connectix which were later acquired by Microsoft.
[src:vagrant/virtualbox] Specifically, InnoTek developed the "additions" code in both Windows Virtual PC and Microsoft Virtual Server, which enables various host–guest OS interactions like shared clipboards or dynamic viewport resizing.
[src:vagrant/virtualbox] Sun Microsystems acquired InnoTek in February 2008.
[src:vagrant/virtualbox] Following the acquisition of Sun Microsystems by Oracle Corporation in January 2010, the product was re-branded as "Oracle VM VirtualBox".
[src:vagrant/virtualbox] In December 2019, VirtualBox removed support for software-based virtualization and exclusively performs hardware-assisted virtualization.
[src:vagrant/virtualbox] In August 2025, VirtualBox started fully supporting ARM virtualization.
[src:vagrant/virtualbox] The core package, since version 4 in December 2010, is free software under GNU General Public License version 2 (GPLv2).
[src:vagrant/virtualbox] A supplementary package, under a proprietary license, adds support for USB 2.0 and 3.0 devices, Remote Desktop Protocol (RDP), disk encryption, NVMe, and Preboot Execution Environment (PXE).
[src:vagrant/virtualbox] This package is called "VirtualBox Oracle VM VirtualBox extension pack".
[src:vagrant/virtualbox] It includes closed-source components, so it is not source-available.
[src:vagrant/virtualbox] The license is called *Personal Use and Evaluation License (PUEL)*.
[src:vagrant/virtualbox] It allows gratis access for personal use, educational use, and evaluation.
[src:vagrant/virtualbox] Since VirtualBox version 5.1.30, Oracle defines personal use as installation on a single computer for non-commercial purposes.
[src:vagrant/virtualbox] Prior to version 4, there were two different packages of the VirtualBox software.
[src:vagrant/virtualbox] The full package was offered gratis under the PUEL, with licenses for other commercial deployment purchasable from Oracle.
[src:vagrant/virtualbox] A second package called the *VirtualBox Open Source Edition (OSE)* was released under GPLv2.
[src:vagrant/virtualbox] This removed the same proprietary components not available under GPLv2.
[src:vagrant/virtualbox] Since September 9, 2011, building the BIOS for VirtualBox requires the Open Watcom compiler, which is released under the Sybase Open Watcom Public License.
[src:vagrant/virtualbox] The Open Source Initiative has approved this as "Open Source" but the Free Software Foundation and the Debian Free Software Guidelines do not consider it "free".
[src:vagrant/virtualbox] VirtualBox has experimental support for macOS guests.
[src:vagrant/virtualbox] However, macOS's end user license agreement does not permit running on non-Apple hardware.
[src:vagrant/virtualbox] The operating system enforces this by calling the Apple System Management Controller (SMC), to verify the hardware's authenticity.
[src:vagrant/virtualbox] Users of VirtualBox can load multiple guest OSes under a single host operating-system (host OS).
[src:vagrant/virtualbox] Each guest can be started, paused and stopped independently within its own virtual machine (VM).
[src:vagrant/virtualbox] The user can independently configure each VM and run it under a choice of software-based virtualization or hardware assisted virtualization if the underlying host hardware supports this.
[src:vagrant/virtualbox] The host OS and guest OSs and applications can communicate with each other through a number of mechanisms including a common clipboard and a virtualized network facility.
[src:vagrant/virtualbox] Guest VMs can also directly communicate with each other if configured to do so.
[src:vagrant/virtualbox] VirtualBox supports both Intel's VT-x and AMD's AMD-V hardware-assisted virtualization.
[src:vagrant/virtualbox] Making use of these facilities, VirtualBox can run each guest VM in its own separate address-space; the guest OS ring 0 code runs on the host at ring 0 in VMX non-root mode rather than in ring 1.
[src:vagrant/virtualbox] Starting with version 6.1, VirtualBox only supports this method.
[src:vagrant/virtualbox] Until then, VirtualBox specifically supported some guests (including 64-bit guests, SMP guests and certain proprietary OSs) only on hosts with hardware-assisted virtualization.
[src:vagrant/virtualbox] VirtualBox emulates hard disks in three formats: the native *VDI* (Virtual Disk Image), VMware's VMDK, and Microsoft's VHD.
[src:vagrant/virtualbox] It thus supports disks created by other hypervisor software.
[src:vagrant/virtualbox] VirtualBox can also connect to iSCSI targets and to raw partitions on the host, using either as virtual hard disks.
[src:vagrant/virtualbox] VirtualBox emulates IDE (PIIX4 and ICH6 controllers), SCSI, SATA (ICH8M controller), and SAS controllers, to which hard drives can be attached.
[src:vagrant/virtualbox] VirtualBox has supported Open Virtualization Format (OVF) since version 2.2.0 (April 2009).
[src:vagrant/virtualbox] Both ISO images and physical devices connected to the host can be mounted as CD or DVD drives.
[src:vagrant/virtualbox] VirtualBox supports running operating systems from live CDs and DVDs.
[src:vagrant/virtualbox] By default, VirtualBox provides graphics support through a custom virtual graphics-card that is VBE or UEFI GOP compatible.
[src:vagrant/virtualbox] The emulated network cards allow most guest OSs to run without the need to find and install drivers for networking hardware as they are shipped as part of the guest OS.
[src:vagrant/virtualbox] A special paravirtualized network adapter is also available, which improves network performance by eliminating the need to match a specific hardware interface, but requires special driver support in the guest.
[src:vagrant/virtualbox] (Many distributions of Linux ship with this driver included.) By default, VirtualBox uses NAT through which Internet software for end-users such as Firefox or ssh can operate.
[src:vagrant/virtualbox] Bridged networking via a host network adapter or virtual networks between guests can also be configured.
[src:vagrant/virtualbox] Up to 36 network adapters can be attached simultaneously, but only four are configurable through the graphical interface.
[src:vagrant/virtualbox] For a sound card, VirtualBox virtualizes Intel HD Audio, Intel ICH AC'97, and SoundBlaster 16 devices.
[src:vagrant/virtualbox] A USB 1.1 controller is emulated, so that any USB devices attached to the host can be seen in the guest.
[src:vagrant/virtualbox] In the absence of hardware-assisted virtualization, versions 6.0.24 and earlier of VirtualBox made use of a standard software-based virtualization approach.
[src:vagrant/virtualbox] This mode supports 32-bit guest operating systems which run in rings 0 and 3 of the Intel ring architecture.
[src:vagrant/virtualbox] In both cases, VirtualBox uses CSAM and PATM to inspect and patch the offending instructions whenever a fault occurs.
[src:vagrant/virtualbox] VirtualBox also contains a dynamic recompiler, based on QEMU to recompile any real mode or protected mode code entirely (e.g.
[src:vagrant/virtualbox] BIOS code, a DOS guest, or any operating system startup).
[src:vagrant/virtualbox] Using these techniques, VirtualBox could achieve performance comparable to that of VMware in its later versions.
[src:vagrant/virtualbox] The feature was dropped starting with VirtualBox 6.1.
[src:vagrant/virtualbox] While VirtualBox itself is free to use and is distributed under an open source license the VirtualBox Extension Pack is licensed under the VirtualBox Personal Use and Evaluation License (PUEL).
[src:vagrant/virtualbox] Personal use of the extension pack is free but commercial users need to purchase a license.
[src:vagrant/virtualbox] Guest Additions are installed within each guest virtual machine which supports them; the Extension Pack is installed on the host running VirtualBox.
